SIMPLE: interrupt
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interrupt
<hw>In`ter*rupt"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Interrupted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Interrupting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>interruptus</ets>,
p. p. of <ets>interrumpere</ets> to interrupt; <ets>inter</ets> between
+ <ets>rumpere</ets> to break. See <er>Rupture</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To break into, or between; to stop, or hinder by
breaking in upon the course or progress of; to interfere with the
current or motion of; to cause a temporary cessation of; <as>as, to
<ex>interrupt</ex> the remarks of anyone speaking</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do not <qex>interrupt</qex> me in my course.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To divide; to separate; to break the monotony of;
<as>as, the evenness of the road was not <ex>interrupted</ex> by a
single hill</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interrupt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Interrupt
<hw>In`ter*rupt"</hw>, <pos>p. a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>interruptus</ets>,
p. p.]</ety> <def>Broken; interrupted.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interrupted</ent>⟦br⟧
